    "jays": {
      "full_name": "Toronto Blue Jays",
      "league": "MLB",
      "record": "7-10",
      "detail": "4th in AL East",
      "live_strip": null,
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "The reigning AL champs are in freefall&mdash;and last night's loss in Milwaukee proved they haven't figured out how to stop it. <strong>The Blue Jays dropped a heartbreaker to the Brewers 2-1 on Tuesday, their first loss after an extra-inning victory the night before</strong>, a one-game swing that perfectly captures their season so far: tantalizing flashes of the team that won it all, followed by the kind of collapses that make contention feel like a mirage. At 7-10, they're already three games behind in the AL East and sitting in fourth place&mdash;not where defending champions should be in mid-April. The 1-2 record on the road suggests travel hasn't been kind. Vladimir Guerrero Jr. and the lineup showed life in Monday's 7&ndash;10 comeback win, with Varsho and Gim&eacute;nez delivering in the clutch, but one night later they couldn't get the bats going when it mattered. The pitching has been the real culprit&mdash;Dylan Cease took the loss yesterday, and the bullpen continues to hemorrhage leads. <strong>They head back to Milwaukee today for the rubber match at 12:40 PM ET</strong>, a chance to salvage something from this series and begin climbing out of the hole they've dug. This is when championship teams show their mettle.",
        "updated": "Updated April 15, 2026"
      },
